Looking at A: {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}

Looking at B: {2, 4, 6, 8}

So, the common elements are 2 and 4.

Set A is {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}

Set C is {1, 3, 5, 7, 9}

Common elements are 1, 3, and 5.

Set B is {2, 4, 6, 8}

Set C is {1, 3, 5, 7, 9}

Combining them, we get {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9}.

First expression:

A ∩ B = {2,4}

A ∩ C = {1,3,5}

Union of these is {1,2,3,4,5} which is A.

Second expression:

B ∪ C = {1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9}

A ∩ (B ∪ C) = {1,2,3,4,5} which is A.
